What is a seizure

Focal seizure with impaired awareness

Absence seizure

Post seizure amnesia

  • Recurrence of more than one unprovoked (or reflex) seizures
  • There are many recognised epilepsy syndromes, which are differentiated based on seizure type/s, genetic or metabolic markers, brain structure and other factors age at onset, or frequency of seizures
  • Classifying a patients syndrome requires monitoring their seizures
  • Generalised seizures simultaneously begin in, or rapidly engage, both hemispheres of the brain.
  • Focal seizures begin in a localised region of brain tissue, which can be identified on the basis of electrical recordings, although they may spread to implicate both sides of the brain (focal to bilateral seizure).
  • Seizures are also classified based on their symptoms; for example, motor seizures may induce muscle spasms (myoclonic seizure), or muscle stiffening followed by spasms (tonic-clonic seizures). Non- motor seizures can induce behaviour arrest, cognitive and emotional symptoms, or loss of awareness.

Emergent properties of the brains structural and/or functional networks that lead to pathological synchronization of cortical activity

So Why Are Seizures a Problem?

  • Seizures can be infrequent, sometimes only one or two a year
  • Seizure symptoms might be subtle or cause forgetfulness
  • Seizures or seizure-like symptoms can have a range of underlying causes

So Why Are Seizures a Problem?

Seizures even small seizures make it dangerous for people going about their normal daily activities

  • Driving
  • Certain jobs may be too dangerous
  • Serious injuries may result

EEG for epilepsy

  • Diagnosis
    • Capture electrographic correlate of a clinical seizure
    • Capture subclinical epileptiform discharges
    • Often inconclusive, especially for routine (1 hr) EEG
  • Management:
    • Determine region of seizure onset
    • Assess treatment efficacy

Are seizures random?

  • Unpredictable but do not show Poisson (random) dynamics
  • Occur in clusters and cycles
  • Individuals patterns of seizure timing are unique for them
  • Risk factors are also unique
